summary:
The Security Council:

Reaffirms previous resolutions on Afghanistan, particularly 1386 (2001), 1510 (2003), 2011 (2011), and 2041 (2012);

Reaffirms resolutions on terrorism, including 1267 (1999), 1368 (2001), and 1988 (2011);

Recalls resolutions on protection of civilians, women, and children in armed conflict;

Reaffirms commitment to Afghanistan's sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity, and national unity;

Recognizes Afghan authorities' responsibility for security and law and order, and ISAF's role in assisting the Afghan Government;

Underlines the importance of strengthening Afghan ownership and leadership in governance;

Welcomes conclusions of International Conference on Afghanistan in Bonn and Tokyo Conference;

Recognizes interconnected challenges in Afghanistan, including security, governance, human rights, and development;

Stresses need for Afghan Government to fight corruption and promote transparency;

Welcomes long-term commitments of international partners to support Afghanistan beyond transition;

Underlines significance of agreement to transfer security responsibility to Afghan Government by end of 2014;

Acknowledges progress and challenges in security sector reform and governance;

Welcomes support and assistance extended to Afghan National Police;

Urges continued professional training measures to ensure Afghan capability to assume security responsibilities.
The Security Council:

Welcomes the Chicago Summit Joint Declaration on Afghanistan, which stresses a long-term commitment to lasting peace, security, and stability in Afghanistan beyond 2014.

Notes the responsibility of the Government of Afghanistan to sustain a sufficient and capable Afghan National Security Force (ANSF), supported by the international community.

Welcomes the decision of the international community to support the training, equipping, financing, and capability development of the ANSF beyond the end of the transition period.

Notes regional initiatives on Afghanistan, such as the Istanbul Process on Regional Security and Cooperation for a Secure and Stable Afghanistan.

Recognizes the importance of the contribution of neighboring and regional partners to the stabilization of Afghanistan.

Stresses the central and impartial role of the United Nations in promoting peace and stability in Afghanistan.
